        <Parent_String>pens (drawing and writing implements) [300022452], drafting, drawing and writing equipment by specific type [300168215], equipment for drafting, drawing, and writing [300168214], image-making equipment [300162803], equipment by process [300024659], equipment [300122241], Tools and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300022238], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Pens made from the shafts of wing feathers or quills of geese, swans, ravens, eagles, owls, hawks, turkeys, and other birds. The tubular quill holds a reservoir of ink and the end may be cut into a pen point with various types of tips. Until the perfection of the metal pen point, the quill pen had historically been the most frequently used instrument for applying liquid media to a drawing surface. The supple tip of the quill can be found in various degrees of stiffness, which permit a wide range of strokes from soft thin lines to bold broad lines.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000026701/Mayer, Dictionary of Art Terms and Techniques (1969)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Pennen die zijn gemaakt van de schachten van slag- of staartpennen van diverse vogels.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052381/Van Dale Engels-Nederlands (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>在柄桿上裝有鳥類翅膀羽毛的筆，例如鵝、天鵝、烏鴉、鷹、貓頭鷹、隼、火雞以及其他鳥類的羽毛。羽毛柄為管狀，可儲存墨水，其末端可切割以製成不同種類的筆尖。在金屬筆尖發展成熟之前，羽毛筆是古人最常用於沾取液體以在表面上進行繪製的工具。羽毛筆尖易於彎曲的特性可帶來多種不同軟硬程度，因此可產生更為多樣的筆觸，包括柔軟細緻的線條與大膽厚重的線條。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Canetas feitas de hastes de penas de asas ou penas de gansos, cisnes, corvos, águias, corujas, falcões, perus e outras aves. A pena tubular contém um reservatório de tinta e a ponta pode ser cortada em ponta de caneta com vários tipos de pontas. Até a perfeição da ponta da caneta de metal, a caneta de pena historicamente era o instrumento mais usado para aplicar mídia líquida em uma superfície de desenho. A ponta flexível da pena pode ser encontrada em vários graus de rigidez, o que permite uma ampla gama de traços, desde linhas finas e suaves até linhas largas e ousadas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
